</media><newline/>
<m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167793551299">
<problem id="fs-id1167793551302">
<para id="fs-id1167793551304"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msqrt><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow></m:msqrt><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mtext>and</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1167793545637">
<problem id="fs-id1167793545640">
<para id="fs-id1167793545642"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mtext>cos</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>−1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>y</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>−1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>−1</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mtext>and</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1167793543511"><para id="fs-id1167793543512"><newline/>
<media id="fs-id1167793543516" alt="This figure is has two graphs. They are the equations y=arccos(x) and y=arcsin (x). The graphs intersect, forming two regions. The first region is bounded to the left by x=-1. The second region is bounded to the right by x=1. Both regions are shaded.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/CNX_Calc_Figure_06_01_237.jpg"/>
</media><newline/>
<m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>−2</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:msqrt><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msqrt><m:mo>−</m:mo><m:mi>π</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<para id="fs-id1167793477060">For the following exercises, find the exact area of the region bounded by the given equations if possible. If you are unable to determine the intersection points analytically, use a calculator to approximate the intersection points with three decimal places and determine the approximate area of the region.</para>
<exercise id="fs-id1167793477066">
